CompletableFuture = a promise of a future result that you can chain operations on.

<pre><code>// Run async task
CompletableFuture&lt;Route&gt; routeFuture = CompletableFuture
    .supplyAsync(() -> routeService.optimize(delivery), executor);

// Chain transformations
CompletableFuture&lt;ETA&gt; etaFuture = routeFuture
    .thenApply(route -> etaCalculator.calculate(route));

// Handle errors
CompletableFuture&lt;ETA&gt; safeFuture = etaFuture
    .exceptionally(ex -> ETA.unknown());

// Combine two independent futures
CompletableFuture&lt;Route&gt; route = getRouteAsync(deliveryId);
CompletableFuture&lt;Driver&gt; driver = getDriverAsync(driverId);

CompletableFuture&lt;DispatchPlan&gt; plan = route.thenCombine(driver,
    (r, d) -> new DispatchPlan(r, d));
// Both execute in PARALLEL, combined when both complete</code></pre>

When two or more threads access shared mutable state concurrently, the result is undefined without coordination. Synchronization ensures that only one thread at a time executes a critical section.

<strong>The problem:</strong> count++ is not atomic. It is three operations: read, increment, write. Two threads can interleave these steps and produce incorrect results.

<pre><code>// Without synchronization — race condition
class Counter {
    private int value = 0;
    public void increment() { value++; } // read → add → write (3 ops)
    public int get() { return value; }
}

// Thread A: read 5
// Thread B: read 5
// Thread A: write 6
// Thread B: write 6  ← lost update! Expected 7, got 6</code></pre>

ReentrantLock provides the same mutual exclusion as synchronized but with additional capabilities: timed locking, interruptible locking, and fairness.

<pre><code>import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

public class DeliveryQueue {
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    private final List&lt;Delivery&gt; queue = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    public void enqueue(Delivery d) {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            queue.add(d);
        } finally {
            lock.unlock(); // ALWAYS in finally — never skip unlock
        }
    }

    // Timed lock — try for 100ms, give up if busy
    public boolean tryEnqueue(Delivery d) throws InterruptedException {
        if (lock.tryLock(100, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS)) {
            try {
                queue.add(d);
                return true;
            } finally {
                lock.unlock();
            }
        }
        return false; // Could not acquire — caller decides what to do
    }
}</code></pre>

<strong>When to use ReentrantLock over synchronized:</strong>
• You need <code>tryLock()</code> to avoid blocking indefinitely
• You need to interrupt a thread waiting for the lock
• You need to check if the lock is currently held (<code>isLocked()</code>)
• You need fair ordering (FIFO for waiting threads)

Most caches and registries are read far more often than written. ReadWriteLock allows multiple concurrent readers but exclusive access for writers.

<pre><code>import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantReadWriteLock;

public class RouteCache {
    private final ReentrantReadWriteLock rwLock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();
    private final Map&lt;String, Route&gt; cache = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

    // Multiple threads can read simultaneously
    public Route get(String routeId) {
        rwLock.readLock().lock();
        try {
            return cache.get(routeId);
        } finally {
            rwLock.readLock().unlock();
        }
    }

    // Only one thread can write — blocks all readers while writing
    public void put(String routeId, Route route) {
        rwLock.writeLock().lock();
        try {
            cache.put(routeId, route);
        } finally {
            rwLock.writeLock().unlock();
        }
    }
}

// Modern alternative: StampedLock (Java 8+) — optimistic reads
import java.util.concurrent.locks.StampedLock;

public class OptimisticRouteCache {
    private final StampedLock sl = new StampedLock();

    public Route get(String id) {
        long stamp = sl.tryOptimisticRead(); // No lock acquired
        Route route = cache.get(id);
        if (sl.validate(stamp)) return route; // Still valid — no write occurred
        // Fallback to read lock if optimistic read failed
        stamp = sl.readLock();
        try {
            return cache.get(id);
        } finally {
            sl.unlockRead(stamp);
        }
    }
}</code></pre>

<strong>Read-to-write ratio matters:</strong>
• &gt;80% reads → ReadWriteLock saves significant contention
• &lt;50% reads → ReentrantLock is simpler and often faster (less overhead)
• Extremely high read throughput → StampedLock optimistic reads eliminate even read-lock overhead

A deadlock occurs when two or more threads are each waiting for a lock held by another, forming a cycle.

<pre><code>// Classic deadlock — two threads, two locks, opposite order
public void transferA(Account from, Account to, int amount) {
    synchronized (from) {        // Thread 1 acquires 'from'
        synchronized (to) {      // Thread 1 waits for 'to'
            from.debit(amount);
            to.credit(amount);
        }
    }
}

public void transferB(Account from, Account to, int amount) {
    synchronized (to) {          // Thread 2 acquires 'to'
        synchronized (from) {    // Thread 2 waits for 'from' — DEADLOCK!
            from.debit(amount);
            to.credit(amount);
        }
    }
}</code></pre>

<strong>Prevention strategies:</strong>

<strong>1. Lock ordering</strong> — always acquire locks in a consistent global order:
<pre><code>public void transfer(Account a, Account b, int amount) {
    Account first  = a.id() &lt; b.id() ? a : b; // Consistent order by ID
    Account second = a.id() &lt; b.id() ? b : a;
    synchronized (first) {
        synchronized (second) {
            first.debit(amount);
            second.credit(amount);
        }
    }
}</code></pre>

<strong>2. Lock timeout</strong> — use tryLock() and back off:
<pre><code>if (lockA.tryLock(50, MILLISECONDS) &amp;&amp; lockB.tryLock(50, MILLISECONDS)) {
    try { /* execute */ }
    finally { lockA.unlock(); lockB.unlock(); }
} else {
    // Back off and retry
}</code></pre>

<strong>3. Avoid nested locks</strong> — the simplest prevention is to not hold a lock while acquiring another.

The core concept of the JMM is <strong>happens-before</strong>. If action A happens-before action B, then A's effects are guaranteed to be visible to B.

<strong>Built-in happens-before rules:</strong>

1. <strong>Program order:</strong> Each action in a thread happens-before every subsequent action in that same thread
2. <strong>Monitor unlock → lock:</strong> Releasing a monitor lock happens-before any subsequent acquisition of the same lock
3. <strong>Volatile write → read:</strong> A write to a volatile field happens-before every subsequent read of that same field
4. <strong>Thread start:</strong> <code>Thread.start()</code> happens-before any action in the started thread
5. <strong>Thread join:</strong> All actions in a thread happen-before <code>Thread.join()</code> returns
6. <strong>Transitivity:</strong> If A happens-before B and B happens-before C, then A happens-before C

<pre><code>// Example — monitor unlock → lock guarantee
class SharedState {
    private int x = 0;
    private boolean ready = false;

    // Thread A
    public synchronized void writeData() {
        x = 42;
        ready = true;
    } // unlock happens here

    // Thread B
    public synchronized void readData() {
        // lock happens here — guaranteed to see x=42 and ready=true
        if (ready) System.out.println(x); // always prints 42
    }
}</code></pre>

Without happens-before, a write in Thread A may never become visible to Thread B.

<pre><code>// ❌ Visibility bug — JVM may cache 'running' in a register
class Worker {
    private boolean running = true; // No visibility guarantee!

    public void run() {
        while (running) { // May loop forever — sees stale cached value
            processNext();
        }
    }

    public void stop() { running = false; } // Written in another thread
}

// ✅ volatile — write is immediately flushed, read always from main memory
class Worker {
    private volatile boolean running = true;

    public void run() {
        while (running) { // Always reads fresh value from main memory
            processNext();
        }
    }

    public void stop() { running = false; }
}</code></pre>

<strong>volatile guarantees:</strong>
• Writes are immediately visible to all threads (no CPU cache stale reads)
• Reads always go to main memory
• Establishes a happens-before between the write and subsequent reads

<strong>volatile does NOT guarantee:</strong>
• Atomicity of compound operations (read-modify-write is still not atomic)

The JVM and CPU can reorder independent instructions for performance. This is invisible within a single thread but visible across threads.

<pre><code>// JVM is free to reorder these (within the same thread, result is the same)
int a = 1;
int b = 2;
int c = a + b;
// Could execute as: b=2, a=1, c=a+b — no observable difference to Thread A
// But Thread B might see b=2 before a=1!

// Double-checked locking — BROKEN before Java 5 due to reordering
public class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance; // NOT volatile

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {          // Check 1
            synchronized (Singleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {  // Check 2
                    instance = new Singleton(); // PROBLEM: partially constructed object!
                    // new Singleton() is: allocate memory, write reference, initialise fields
                    // JVM may reorder to: allocate memory, write reference (instance != null now!), initialise fields later
                    // Thread B sees non-null instance but uninitialised fields!
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

// ✅ Fixed with volatile — volatile write prevents reordering
private static volatile Singleton instance;
// The volatile write to 'instance' cannot be reordered before field initialisation</code></pre>

An object is <strong>safely published</strong> when it is made visible to other threads in a way that guarantees they see a fully initialised object.

<pre><code>// ❌ Unsafe publication — other threads may see partially initialised object
class Cache {
    public volatile String[] data; // volatile reference, but array content not protected!

    public void refresh() {
        String[] newData = loadFromDB(); // load complete data
        data = newData; // publish — but array writes might not be ordered!
    }
}

// ✅ Safe publication patterns:

// 1. final field (guaranteed visible after constructor)
class Config {
    private final Map&lt;String, String&gt; settings; // final = safely published
    Config(Map&lt;String, String&gt; settings) {
        this.settings = Collections.unmodifiableMap(settings);
    }
}

// 2. Volatile reference to immutable object
volatile ImmutableConfig config; // volatile write establishes happens-before
config = new ImmutableConfig(newSettings); // entire object visible after write

// 3. Atomic reference
AtomicReference&lt;Config&gt; configRef = new AtomicReference&lt;&gt;();
configRef.set(new ImmutableConfig(newSettings)); // atomic + visible

// 4. synchronized publication
synchronized void updateConfig(Config c) { this.config = c; }
synchronized Config getConfig() { return this.config; }</code></pre>
